# National AI Fraud Detection Platform
**TELUS · Senior AI Product Manager · 2024 – Present**

---

## The problem

TELUS had a fraud exposure problem that was growing faster than the manual processes designed to catch it. The existing approach relied heavily on reactive, rules-based review — slow, inconsistent, and expensive. The business did not have a clear picture of total fraud risk across its device portfolio, and by the time fraud was identified, the financial damage had compounded.

The deeper issue: fraud prevention was being treated as a cost centre rather than a strategic product domain. Nobody had owned it end-to-end across devices, channels, and customer journeys at once.

---

## My role

I was brought in to own the full product lifecycle from the ground up — diagnosis, strategy, roadmap, cross-functional delivery, and executive reporting.

This was not a "PM assigned to a team already building something" situation. I identified the opportunity, quantified it, built the business case, secured executive buy-in, defined the technical architecture with engineering, and drove delivery.

---

## What I diagnosed

- **$4M+ in annual fraud exposure** identified across 1,250+ devices once I mapped the full fraud surface
- Existing manual processes were catching only a fraction of actual fraudulent activity
- Operational costs for fraud review were disproportionately high relative to the value recovered
- Customer friction from false positives was creating secondary CX damage on top of the fraud cost itself

---

## What I built

A national AI fraud detection platform designed to operate across the full customer lifecycle — retail, digital, and call centre channels simultaneously.

**Core design decisions:**

- **Multi-channel architecture:** I defined the product to work across retail, digital, and call centre environments rather than solving for one channel and retrofitting. This was a harder technical scope but the only way to get a complete picture.
- **End-to-end ownership model:** Rather than building a detection tool and handing it to operations, I designed the product so that fraud prevention was embedded into existing operational workflows rather than sitting beside them. This was the key insight that enabled the 90% cost reduction.
- **ML-powered detection with human-in-the-loop escalation:** The system flags, prioritizes, and routes. It does not operate without human review on high-stakes decisions — a responsible AI principle I insisted on.

**Roadmap sequencing:**

I drove a phased rollout across channel environments, deliberately sequencing by risk level and operational readiness. I aligned go-to-market sequencing with engineering capacity and CX risk trade-offs to avoid friction spikes during rollout.

